Musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive impairments can cause difficulty in movement and have negative effects on psychological health. Clinical gait analysis is an important tool for early diagnosis and treatment, but traditionally relies on expensive optical motion capture systems. Recent advances in computer vision and deep learning have opened the door to more accessible and cost-effective alternatives. In this paper, we introduce a novel transformer network to estimate critical gait parameters from RGB videos captured by a single-view camera. Empirical evaluations on a public dataset of cerebral palsy patients indicate that our proposed framework surpasses current state-of-the-art approaches and shows significant improvements in predicting general gait parameters (including walking speed, Gait Deviation Index - GDI, and knee flexion angle at maximum extension), while utilizing fewer parameters and alleviating the need for manual feature extraction.

Musculoskeletal diseases and cognitive impairments can make it difficult to move around, and they can also have a negative impact on mental health. In this paper, we present a new transformer network that can estimate critical gait parameters from RGB videos captured by a single-view camera. Our framework is able to surpass current state-of-the-art approaches and shows significant improvements in predicting general gait parameters (such as walking speed, Gait Deviation Index - GDI, and knee flexion angle at maximum extension), while utilizing fewer parameters and eliminating the need for manual feature extraction.
